    </script><meta content="LearningHindi" property="fb:admins" /><meta content="Learning Hindi!" property="og:site_name" /><meta content="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/42603252487/lesson-134-the-verb-लगन-lagnaa-part-1" property="og:url" /><meta content="article" property="og:type" /><meta content="In today&rsquo;s lesson we&rsquo;re going to begin to look at the Hindi verb &#2354;&#2327;&#2344;&#2366; lagnaa. This is one of the most common verbs in Hindi and unfortunately it can also be real tricky to understand and translate sometimes, it just has so many meanings! So let&rsquo;s get straight into it, are you ready?


 The most literal meaning of &#2354;&#2327;&#2344;&#2366; lagnaa is &lsquo;to be attached&rsquo; or 'to be stuck&rsquo;, so we might say something like&hellip;





&#2338;&#2325;&#2381;&#2325;&#2344; &#2344;&#2361;&#2368;&#2306; &#2354;&#2327;&#2366; &#2341;&#2366; dhakkan naheen lagaa thaa - The lid was not attached


 That&rsquo;s easy enough yeah? Now you might be surprised to hear that in Hindi we can use this verb to talk about feelings. How does that work? Well let me show you an example to start with&hellip;


 





&#2350;&#2369;&#2333;&#2375; &#2336;&#2306;&#2337; &#2354;&#2327; &#2352;&#2361;&#2368; &#2361;&#2376; mujhe thand lag rahee hai - I am (feeling) cold


 What&rsquo;s happening here? Well let&rsquo;s look at the sentence literally; we&rsquo;re saying &ldquo;to me cold is attached&rdquo;. This may seem like a very odd way of saying &ldquo;I&rsquo;m cold&rdquo; in Hindi but that&rsquo;s just how we say it, that coldness is attached to you. If it helps you remember imagine a great big cold monster attaching himself to you!


 Notice as well that here we&rsquo;re using the feminine form of the verb to agree with the feminine word &#2336;&#2306;&#2337; thand. A few other feelings like this follow the same pattern&hellip;





&#2313;&#2360;&#2325;&#2379; &#2346;&#2381;&#2351;&#2366;&#2360; &#2354;&#2327;&#2368; usko pyaas lagee - He was (feeling) thirsty


 Again we&rsquo;ve used exactly the same construction, we&rsquo;re literally saying &ldquo;to him thirst was attached&rdquo;. Strangle hey! One more then&hellip;





&#2310;&#2342;&#2350;&#2368; &#2325;&#2379; &#2352;&#2366;&#2325;&#2381;&#2359;&#2360; &#2360;&#2375; &#2337;&#2352; &#2354;&#2327;&#2366;&nbsp; aadmee ko raakshas se dar lagaa - The man was scared of the monster


 Here we&rsquo;re using the word &#2337;&#2352; dar - 'fear&rsquo; to literally say &ldquo;to the man by the monster fear was attached&rdquo;, which is quite a mouthful! Can you understand and follow the sentence? Feel free to ask in comments below if you&rsquo;re at all confused!


 There&rsquo;s a few other words we can use like this including &#2349;&#2370;&#2326; bhookh - hunger (fem) and &#2327;&#2352;&#2350;&#2368; garmee - heat (fem). Another word that follows the same pattern is &#2330;&#2379;&#2335; cot - injury (fem). We use &#2330;&#2379;&#2335; &#2354;&#2327;&#2344;&#2366; cot lagnaa to mean 'to be injured&rsquo;. The 'thing&rsquo; that gets injured or hurt is followed by a &#2325;&#2379; ko and the verb is always feminine (since it always agrees with &#2330;&#2379;&#2335; cot). For example&hellip;





&#2350;&#2342;&#2342;! &#2350;&#2369;&#2333;&#2375; &#2330;&#2379;&#2335; &#2354;&#2327;&#2340;&#2368; &#2361;&#2376; madad! mujhe cot lagtee hai - Help! I am hurt


 We can also use &#2354;&#2327;&#2344;&#2366; lagnaa to mean 'seems&rsquo; in sentences where we think something is true. We might say&hellip; 





&#2351;&#2361; &#2360;&#2361;&#2368; &#2354;&#2327;&#2340;&#2366; &#2361;&#2376; yeh sahee lagtaa hai - This seems correct





&#2350;&#2369;&#2333;&#2375; &#2354;&#2327;&#2340;&#2366; &#2361;&#2376; &#2325;&#2367; &#2361;&#2367;&#2344;&#2381;&#2342;&#2368; &#2348;&#2361;&#2369;&#2340; &#2325;&#2336;&#2367;&#2344; &#2361;&#2376; mujhe lagtaa hai ki hindee bahut kathin hai - To me it seems that Hindi is very difficult


 Can you follow this sentence? Don&rsquo;t forget that &#2325;&#2367; ki means 'that&rsquo;!


 Phew ok, I recon that&rsquo;s enough for today. Can you see already how versatile this verb &#2354;&#2327;&#2344;&#2366; lagnaa is, it&rsquo;s already got so many meanings and uses! In Part 2 we&rsquo;ll be learning even more about this verb so be sure to check it out here.


 To check your understanding of the lesson today try translating these sentences into Hindi. Leave your answers in the comments section below especially if you&rsquo;re not completely sure - I&rsquo;m here to help!


 
 The letter is attached


 Yesterday I was so hot


 Are you hungry?


 Her hand was injured


 To me it seems that Amit is a good man



 So be sure to give them a go!


 Click here to go to Lesson #135 The Verb &#2354;&#2327;&#2344;&#2366; lagnaa Part 2.


